  "prompt": "At what point do a sperm cell and an egg become a boy or a girl?",
  "response": "The genetic sex of an embryo is determined at fertilization, when the sperm and egg combine. The sperm carries either an X or Y chromosome, while the egg always carries an X chromosome. If a sperm with a Y chromosome fertilizes the egg, the resulting embryo will be genetically male (XY). If a sperm with an X chromosome fertilizes the egg, the embryo will be genetically female (XX).\n\nThe development of physical sex characteristics begins around 6-7 weeks of pregnancy, when the gonads start to differentiate based on the presence or absence of the SRY gene on the Y chromosome. However, external genitalia don't become distinctly male or female until around 12-13 weeks of pregnancy.",
